categories.pattern: HOW DO I CHECK MY APPLICATION STATUS
categories.template: You can check your status at the USCIS Case Status Online tool at https://egov.uscis.gov/casestatus/landing.do. You'll need your receipt number (starts with MSC, EAC, WAC, etc.).

categories.pattern: WHAT IS MY RECEIPT NUMBER
categories.template: Your receipt number is a 13-character code that starts with three letters (like MSC, EAC, WAC, NBC, etc.) followed by 10 numbers. You can find it on any official USCIS correspondence or notices.

categories.pattern: HOW LONG DOES * TAKE
categories.template:
Processing times vary by application type and service center:

• **N-400 (Naturalization)**: 12-18 months
• **I-485 (Green Card)**: 16-24 months
• **I-765 (Work Authorization)**: 3-5 months
• **I-131 (Travel Document)**: 4-6 months

Check current processing times at https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/

categories.pattern: WHAT DOCUMENTS DO I NEED FOR *
categories.template:
Required documents vary by application type. Common documents include:

• **Form-specific requirements** (check the form instructions)
• **Identity documents** (passport, driver's license)
• **Supporting evidence** (birth certificates, marriage certificates)
• **Photos** (passport-style photos)
• **Filing fees** (check current fee schedule)

Refer to the specific form instructions on uscis.gov for complete requirements.

categories.pattern: CAN I TRAVEL WHILE MY * IS PENDING
categories.template:
Travel while applications are pending depends on your situation:

• **With valid visa/status**: Generally permitted
• **Adjustment of Status (I-485)**: Need Advance Parole (I-131)
• **Naturalization (N-400)**: Usually no restrictions
• **Asylum cases**: Consult an attorney before travel

⚠️ **Important**: Always consult with an immigration attorney before international travel with pending applications.

categories.pattern: WHAT IS RFE
categories.template:
**RFE (Request for Evidence)** means USCIS needs additional documentation to make a decision on your case.

**What to do:**
• Read the RFE notice carefully
• Gather all requested documents
• Submit response by the deadline (usually 87 days)
• Include a cover letter explaining each document

**Important**: Failure to respond may result in case denial.

categories.pattern: HOW TO EXPEDITE MY APPLICATION
categories.template:
You may request expedited processing for:

**Eligible reasons:**
• Severe financial loss
• Emergency situations
• Humanitarian reasons
• Nonprofit organization interests
• USCIS error

**How to request:**
• Call USCIS Contact Center: 1-800-375-5283
• Submit written request with evidence
• Explain qualifying circumstances

**Note**: Expedite requests are rarely approved and require compelling evidence.

categories.pattern: USCIS CONTACT INFORMATION
categories.template:
**USCIS Contact Information:**

• **Customer Service**: 1-800-375-5283 (TTY: 1-800-767-1833)
• **Hours**: Monday-Friday, 8 AM - 6 PM (local time)
• **Online**: uscis.gov
• **Case Status**: https://egov.uscis.gov/casestatus/
• **Processing Times**: https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/

**For emergencies outside business hours**, visit your local USCIS field office.

categories.pattern: WHAT ARE USCIS PROCESSING TIMES FOR MY CASE
categories.template:
Find estimated processing times on the **USCIS Processing Times tool** for your specific form and office:

• Visit: https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/
• Select your form type and filing location
• Processing times are updated monthly
• Times vary by service center and case complexity

**Note**: These are estimates only. Your case may take longer or shorter than posted times.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I CHANGE MY ADDRESS WITH USCIS
categories.template:
Update your address online using the **USCIS Change of Address tool**:

• **Online**: https://egov.uscis.gov/coa/displayCOAForm.do
• **By Phone**: 1-800-375-5283
• **Form AR-11**: Available for download at uscis.gov

⚠️ **Important**: All non-citizens must report a new address within **10 days** of moving. Failure to do so may affect your case.

categories.pattern: I LOST MY GREEN CARD WHAT DO I DO
categories.template:
File **Form I-90, Application to Replace Permanent Resident Card**:

• **Online Filing**: Recommended at uscis.gov
• **By Mail**: Download form and mail to USCIS
• **Required Documents**: Copy of previous green card (if available), identity documents
• **Fee**: Check current I-90 filing fee

**Processing Time**: Typically 10-13 months. You may request expedited processing for travel emergencies.

categories.pattern: WHAT DOCUMENTS DO I NEED FOR NATURALIZATION
categories.template:
**Required Documents for Naturalization (N-400):**

• **Form N-400** (completed and signed)
• **Copy of green card** (front and back)
• **Two passport-style photos**
• **Copy of marriage certificate** (if applicable)
• **Divorce decrees** (if applicable)
• **Tax returns** (last 5 years)
• **Travel records** (trips outside US)

**Additional documents may be required** based on your specific situation. Review Form N-400 instructions carefully.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I APPLY FOR A WORK PERMIT
categories.template:
File **Form I-765, Application for Employment Authorization**:

• **Online Filing**: Available at uscis.gov (recommended)
• **By Mail**: Download form and supporting documents
• **Required**: Copy of I-94, passport, supporting evidence for your category
• **Photos**: Two passport-style photos
• **Fee**: Check current I-765 filing fee

**Processing Time**: Typically 3-5 months. Expedite requests available for certain circumstances.

categories.pattern: WHEN IS MY BIOMETRICS APPOINTMENT
categories.template:
**USCIS will mail you a biometrics appointment notice** after your application is received:

• **Timeline**: Usually 2-4 weeks after filing
• **Notice Contents**: Date, time, and location
• **What to Bring**: Photo ID and appointment notice
• **Rescheduling**: Call USCIS if you cannot attend

**Haven't received your notice?** Contact USCIS if it's been more than 4 weeks since filing.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I SCHEDULE AN INFOPASS APPOINTMENT
categories.template:
**InfoPass appointments are no longer available.** Instead:

• **Call USCIS**: 1-800-375-5283 for case inquiries
• **Online Account**: Submit case inquiries through your USCIS account
• **Emergency Appointments**: Available for urgent situations only
• **Field Office Visits**: Limited to scheduled appointments only

**For most inquiries**, use the USCIS Contact Center or online services.

categories.pattern: HOW CAN I CONTACT A LIVE USCIS AGENT
categories.template:
**Contact USCIS Customer Service:**

• **Phone**: 1-800-375-5283
• **TTY**: 1-800-767-1833 (hearing impaired)
• **Hours**: Monday–Friday, 8 AM–8 PM ET
• **Wait Times**: Typically 30-60 minutes

**Tips for faster service:**
• Have your receipt number ready
• Call early in the morning
• Use online services when possible

categories.pattern: HOW DO I PAY MY USCIS FEES
categories.template:
**USCIS Fee Payment Options:**

• **Online**: Credit/debit card through uscis.gov (most forms)
• **Check/Money Order**: Made payable to 'U.S. Department of Homeland Security'
• **Bank Transfer**: Available for some online filings

**Important**: Check current fee amounts on uscis.gov before payment. Fees change periodically and vary by form type.

categories.pattern: WHAT IF MY CASE IS OUTSIDE NORMAL PROCESSING TIMES
categories.template:
**If your case exceeds normal processing times:**

• **Submit a Case Inquiry**: Through your USCIS online account
• **Call USCIS**: 1-800-375-5283 to request status update
• **Required Information**: Receipt number and case details
• **Response Time**: USCIS will respond within 30 days

**Note**: Only submit inquiries if your case is **outside** the posted processing times for your form and office.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I CHECK THE STATUS OF MY GREEN CARD RENEWAL
categories.template:
**Check your I-90 (Green Card Renewal) status:**

• **Online**: https://egov.uscis.gov/casestatus/ with your I-90 receipt number
• **USCIS Account**: Log into your online account for detailed updates
• **Phone**: Call 1-800-375-5283 with receipt number

**Typical Processing**: 10-13 months. You'll receive biometrics and interview notices if required.

categories.pattern: CAN I EXPEDITE MY USCIS APPLICATION
categories.template:
**USCIS allows expedite requests for certain criteria:**

**Eligible Reasons:**
• Severe financial loss to company or person
• Emergency situations
• Humanitarian reasons
• Nonprofit organization furthering cultural/social interests
• USCIS error

**How to Request:**
• Call 1-800-375-5283
• Provide compelling evidence
• Explain qualifying circumstances

⚠️ **Note**: Expedite requests are **rarely approved** and require substantial documentation.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I OBTAIN MY USCIS RECEIPT NUMBER
categories.template:
**Your USCIS receipt number is located:**

• **Notice of Action (Form I-797)**: Top left corner
• **Format**: 3 letters + 10 numbers (e.g., MSC2190012345)
• **Letter Prefixes**: MSC, EAC, WAC, NBC, IOE, etc.
• **Timeline**: Received 2-4 weeks after filing

**Lost your receipt notice?** Contact USCIS at 1-800-375-5283 with your personal information to retrieve it.

categories.pattern: I MADE A MISTAKE ON MY APPLICATION WHAT SHOULD I DO
categories.template:
**If you made an error on your USCIS application:**

• **Before Decision**: Contact USCIS immediately at 1-800-375-5283
• **Provide**: Receipt number and specific error details
• **Documentation**: Submit corrected information in writing
• **Minor Errors**: May be corrected at interview
• **Major Errors**: May require new application

⚠️ **Act Quickly**: Contact USCIS as soon as you discover the mistake.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I CHECK MY ELIGIBILITY FOR CITIZENSHIP
categories.template:
**Check your citizenship eligibility:**

• **USCIS Eligibility Tool**: Available at uscis.gov
• **Form N-400 Instructions**: Detailed eligibility requirements
• **General Requirements**: 5 years as permanent resident (3 if married to US citizen)
• **Physical Presence**: At least 30 months in US during 5-year period
• **Good Moral Character**: Required for eligibility period

**Consult an immigration attorney** for complex situations or questions about eligibility.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I RENEW MY DACA
categories.template:
**DACA Renewal Process:**

• **Forms Required**: I-821D, I-765, and I-765 Worksheet
• **Filing Window**: 150-120 days before current DACA expires
• **Fee**: Check current DACA renewal fee
• **Documents**: Updated evidence of continuous residence
• **Processing Time**: Typically 3-5 months

**Important**: File within the renewal window to avoid gaps in protection. Late renewals may not be accepted.

categories.pattern: WHAT IF I DID NOT RECEIVE MY BIOMETRIC APPOINTMENT LETTER
categories.template:
**If you haven't received your biometrics notice:**

• **Timeline**: Should arrive 2-4 weeks after filing
• **Contact USCIS**: Call 1-800-375-5283 if it's been over 4 weeks
• **Case Inquiry**: Submit online through your USCIS account
• **Address Issues**: Ensure USCIS has your current address

**Bring to appointment**: Photo ID and the appointment notice (when received).

categories.pattern: HOW DO I REPORT FRAUD OR ABUSE
categories.template:
**Report suspected immigration fraud:**

• **Online**: https://www.uscis.gov/report-fraud
• **Phone**: 1-800-375-5283
• **Email**: uscis.fraud@uscis.dhs.gov
• **Types**: Fraudulent documents, fake marriages, unauthorized practice
• **Information Needed**: Detailed description and evidence

**Your report helps protect** the integrity of the immigration system. Reports can be made anonymously.

categories.pattern: WHERE CAN I GET IMMIGRATION FORMS
categories.template:
**Download USCIS forms for free:**

• **Official Website**: https://www.uscis.gov/forms
• **All Forms Available**: N-400, I-485, I-765, I-90, etc.
• **Instructions Included**: Each form comes with detailed instructions
• **Latest Versions**: Always use current form editions

⚠️ **Avoid Third-Party Sites**: Only use official uscis.gov to ensure you have the correct, current forms.

categories.pattern: CAN I TRAVEL WHILE MY APPLICATION IS PENDING
categories.template:
**Travel with pending applications depends on your status:**

• **Valid Visa/Status**: Generally permitted to travel
• **Adjustment of Status (I-485)**: Need **Advance Parole (I-131)** to re-enter
• **Naturalization (N-400)**: Usually no travel restrictions
• **Asylum Cases**: **Consult attorney before travel**

⚠️ **Important**: Always consult with an immigration attorney before international travel with pending applications.

categories.pattern: WHAT HAPPENS AFTER I FILE MY APPLICATION
categories.template:
**After filing your USCIS application:**

**Step 1**: Receive **Receipt Notice (I-797C)** (2-4 weeks)
**Step 2**: **Biometrics Appointment** scheduled (if required)
**Step 3**: **Interview Scheduled** (if required)
**Step 4**: **Decision Issued** (approval, denial, or RFE)

**Timeline varies** by application type and service center. Check processing times at uscis.gov for estimates.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I CHECK MY CITIZENSHIP INTERVIEW DATE
categories.template:
**Check your naturalization interview date:**

• **USCIS Online Account**: Most reliable source for updates
• **Mail Notice**: USCIS will send interview notice by mail
• **Case Status Tool**: https://egov.uscis.gov/casestatus/
• **Timeline**: Usually scheduled 6-12 months after filing N-400

**Interview Notice includes**: Date, time, location, and documents to bring.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I UPDATE MY CASE WITH NEW EVIDENCE
categories.template:
**Submit additional evidence to USCIS:**

• **Online Account**: Upload documents through your USCIS account (preferred)
• **By Mail**: Send to address on your receipt notice
• **Include**: Cover letter explaining documents and receipt number
• **RFE Response**: Follow specific RFE instructions if responding to request

**Important**: Keep copies of all documents sent to USCIS.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I GET HELP IN ANOTHER LANGUAGE
categories.template:
**USCIS language assistance:**

• **Spanish**: Full website and forms available in Spanish
• **Other Languages**: Limited translation services available
• **Interpreters**: Bring qualified interpreter to interviews
• **Forms**: Some forms available in multiple languages
• **Customer Service**: Spanish-speaking agents available

**For complex cases**, consider hiring an immigration attorney who speaks your language.

categories.pattern: WHAT ARE THE FIELDS IN GREEN CARD FORM
categories.template:
**Key fields in Green Card forms (I-485 and I-90):**

**Personal Information:**
• Full legal name (as it appears on documents)
• Date and place of birth
• Country of birth and citizenship
• Social Security Number
• A-Number (if previously assigned)

**Contact Information:**
• Current mailing address
• Physical address (if different)
• Phone number and email

**Immigration History:**
• Date of entry to US
• Current immigration status
• Previous USCIS case numbers
• Travel history (trips outside US)

**Background Information:**
• Employment history
• Education background
• Criminal history (if any)
• Previous marriages/divorces

**Supporting Documents Required:**
• Birth certificate
• Passport photos
• Medical examination (if required)
• Financial support evidence

**Important**: Complete all fields accurately and provide supporting documentation as specified in the form instructions.

categories.pattern: WHAT DOES MY CASE STATUS MEAN
categories.template:
**Common USCIS Case Statuses:**

• **Case Was Received**: USCIS has received your application
• **Case Is Being Actively Reviewed**: Officer is reviewing your case
• **Request for Additional Evidence Was Sent**: You need to submit more documents
• **Interview Was Scheduled**: You'll receive an interview notice
• **Case Was Approved**: Your application has been approved
• **Case Was Denied**: Your application was not approved

Check the USCIS website for detailed explanations of each status.

categories.pattern: WHY HASN'T MY STATUS UPDATED
categories.template:
**Reasons for status delays:**

• **Normal Processing**: Cases update at different stages, not daily
• **Background Checks**: Security clearances can cause delays
• **High Volume**: USCIS processes cases in order received
• **Additional Review**: Complex cases take longer
• **System Updates**: Status updates may be delayed

**Action**: Only contact USCIS if your case is outside normal processing times.

categories.pattern: HOW OFTEN DOES USCIS UPDATE STATUS
categories.template:
**USCIS Status Update Frequency:**

• **Not Daily**: Status doesn't update every day
• **Milestone Updates**: Updates occur at major processing steps
• **Varies by Case**: Some cases update more frequently than others
• **System Delays**: Technical updates may be delayed

**Typical Update Points:**
• Case received
• Biometrics scheduled/completed
• Interview scheduled
• Decision made

**Check weekly** rather than daily for updates.

categories.pattern: CAN I CHECK STATUS WITHOUT RECEIPT NUMBER
categories.template:
**No, you cannot check status without a receipt number.** The receipt number is required to access your case information.

**If you lost your receipt number:**
• **Call USCIS**: 1-800-375-5283 with your personal information
• **Check Email**: USCIS may have sent electronic receipts
• **Review Documents**: Look through all USCIS correspondence
• **Attorney Records**: If you used an attorney, they should have copies

**Receipt numbers start with**: MSC, EAC, WAC, NBC, IOE, etc.

categories.pattern: WHY IS MY CASE TAKING SO LONG
categories.template:
**Common reasons for processing delays:**

• **Background Checks**: FBI name checks can take months
• **RFE Response**: Waiting for your additional evidence
• **Interview Scheduling**: Limited appointment availability
• **Complex Cases**: Require additional review time
• **High Volume**: Service centers processing many cases
• **Administrative Processing**: Additional security clearances

**Check processing times** for your form and service center to see if your case is within normal timeframes.

categories.pattern: WHAT ARE CURRENT PROCESSING TIMES
categories.template:
**Check current processing times:**

• **Official Tool**: https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/
• **Select Your Form**: Choose your application type
• **Select Office**: Choose your filing location
• **Updated Monthly**: Times are refreshed regularly

**Processing times vary by:**
• Form type (N-400, I-485, etc.)
• Service center location
• Case complexity
• Current workload

**Note**: These are estimates only. Your case may take longer or shorter.

categories.pattern: MY CASE IS OUTSIDE PROCESSING TIMES
categories.template:
**If your case exceeds normal processing times:**

• **Submit Case Inquiry**: Through your USCIS online account
• **Call USCIS**: 1-800-375-5283 for status update
• **Provide Information**: Receipt number and case details
• **Response Time**: USCIS will respond within 30 days
• **Congressional Inquiry**: Contact your representative if needed

**Required**: Your case must be **outside** posted processing times before submitting an inquiry.

categories.pattern: DO PROCESSING TIMES INCLUDE WEEKENDS
categories.template:
**USCIS Processing Time Calculations:**

• **Calendar Days**: Processing times are in calendar days, not business days
• **Includes Weekends**: Weekends and holidays are counted
• **From Receipt Date**: Timing starts when USCIS receives your application
• **To Decision Date**: Ends when USCIS makes a decision

**Example**: If processing time is 12 months, it means 12 calendar months from your receipt date, including all weekends and holidays.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I RENEW MY GREEN CARD
categories.template:
**Green Card Renewal Process (Form I-90):**

• **When to Renew**: Within 6 months of expiration
• **Online Filing**: Available at uscis.gov (recommended)
• **Required Documents**: Current green card, photos, supporting evidence
• **Fee**: Check current I-90 filing fee
• **Processing Time**: 10-13 months
• **Biometrics**: May be required

**Important**: Don't wait until your card expires to file for renewal.

categories.pattern: CAN I TRAVEL WITH EXPIRED GREEN CARD
categories.template:
**Travel with Expired Green Card:**

• **Within US**: Expired green card still proves permanent resident status
• **International Travel**: **NOT RECOMMENDED** - airlines may deny boarding
• **Re-entry Issues**: CBP may question your status
• **Better Options**: Get I-551 stamp or file I-90 before travel

**Recommended Actions:**
• **File I-90**: Apply for green card renewal
• **Get I-551 Stamp**: Temporary evidence of permanent residence
• **Avoid Travel**: Until you have valid documentation

**Emergency Travel**: Contact USCIS for guidance on urgent travel needs.

categories.pattern: HOW LONG IS GREEN CARD VALID
categories.template:
**Green Card Validity Periods:**

• **Permanent Residents**: 10 years
• **Conditional Residents**: 2 years (marriage-based, investment-based)
• **Returning Residents**: Varies based on circumstances

**Renewal Timeline:**
• **Start Renewal**: 6 months before expiration
• **Don't Wait**: Processing takes 10-13 months
• **Expired Cards**: Still valid for employment, but not travel

**Conditional Green Cards**: Must file I-751 to remove conditions before expiration.

categories.pattern: WHAT IS THE NATURALIZATION TEST
categories.template:
**Naturalization Test Components:**

**English Test:**
• **Speaking**: Assessed during interview
• **Reading**: Read 1-3 sentences aloud
• **Writing**: Write 1-3 sentences

**Civics Test:**
• **Questions**: Up to 10 questions from 100 possible
• **Pass Score**: Answer 6 out of 10 correctly
• **Topics**: American history and civics
• **Study Materials**: Available at uscis.gov

**Exemptions Available:**
• Age and time as permanent resident
• Medical disabilities
• Check USCIS website for specific exemption criteria

categories.pattern: WHAT HAPPENS AT CITIZENSHIP INTERVIEW
categories.template:
**Naturalization Interview Process:**

**Before Interview:**
• Arrive early with all required documents
• Bring original documents and copies
• Review your N-400 application

**During Interview:**
• **Oath**: Swear to tell the truth
• **Application Review**: Officer reviews your N-400
• **Background Questions**: About your application and background
• **English Test**: Speaking, reading, writing
• **Civics Test**: Up to 10 questions about US history/civics

**After Interview:**
• **Decision**: Approved, denied, or continued
• **Next Steps**: Oath ceremony scheduling (if approved)

**Typical Duration**: 20-30 minutes

categories.pattern: HOW DO I RENEW MY WORK PERMIT
categories.template:
**Work Permit Renewal (Form I-765):**

• **When to File**: 150-180 days before expiration
• **Same Process**: File new I-765 application
• **Required Documents**: Current EAD, supporting evidence, photos
• **Fee**: Full filing fee required
• **Processing Time**: 3-5 months
• **Automatic Extension**: May be available for certain categories

**Don't wait**: File well before your current EAD expires to avoid work authorization gaps.

categories.pattern: CAN I WORK WITHOUT EAD
categories.template:
**Work Authorization Without EAD:**

**Authorized to Work:**
• **US Citizens**: No EAD required
• **Permanent Residents**: Green card authorizes work
• **Certain Visa Holders**: H-1B, L-1, O-1, etc.

**NOT Authorized:**
• **Visitors** (B-1/B-2)
• **Students** without proper authorization
• **Tourists**
• **Most pending applicants** without EAD

**Penalties**: Working without authorization can affect future immigration benefits.

**Check your status** and consult an attorney if unsure about work authorization.

categories.pattern: WHAT IS EAD CATEGORY
categories.template:
**EAD Categories (Form I-765):**

**Common Categories:**
• **(c)(9)**: Adjustment of status applicants (I-485 pending)
• **(a)(12)**: Asylum applicants
• **(c)(8)**: Asylum grantees
• **(a)(10)**: Withholding of removal
• **(c)(33)**: DACA recipients
• **(a)(5)**: Refugees

**Category determines:**
• Eligibility requirements
• Required supporting documents
• Processing times
• Renewal procedures

**Check Form I-765 instructions** for complete list and requirements for each category.

categories.pattern: HOW LONG IS EAD VALID
categories.template:
**EAD Validity Periods:**

**Varies by Category:**
• **Adjustment Applicants**: Usually 2 years
• **Asylum Applicants**: 150 days to 2 years
• **DACA**: 2 years
• **Refugees**: 2-4 years
• **Students (OPT)**: 12 months (STEM: 24 months extension)

**Renewal Required:**
• File new I-765 before expiration
• Start process 150-180 days early
• Some categories have automatic extensions

**Check your EAD card** for exact expiration date and plan renewal accordingly.

categories.pattern: WHAT IF I MISSED MY BIOMETRICS APPOINTMENT
categories.template:
**If you missed your biometrics appointment:**

• **Contact USCIS Immediately**: Call 1-800-375-5283
• **Request Reschedule**: Explain why you missed appointment
• **Valid Reasons**: Medical emergency, military deployment, etc.
• **Documentation**: Provide evidence for your absence
• **Timeline**: Contact USCIS as soon as possible

**Consequences of Missing:**
• Case may be denied for failure to appear
• Processing delays
• May need to refile application

**Don't ignore**: Always contact USCIS if you cannot attend.

categories.pattern: WHAT TO BRING TO BIOMETRICS APPOINTMENT
categories.template:
**Required Items for Biometrics:**

• **Appointment Notice**: Original notice from USCIS
• **Photo ID**: Driver's license, passport, or state ID
• **If Under 14**: Parent/guardian must accompany
• **Interpreter**: If needed, bring qualified interpreter

**Process Takes:**
• **Fingerprints**: Digital fingerprint scanning
• **Photo**: Digital photograph
• **Signature**: Electronic signature capture
• **Duration**: Usually 15-30 minutes

**Arrive Early**: Come 15 minutes before appointment time.

categories.pattern: CAN I RESCHEDULE BIOMETRICS APPOINTMENT
categories.template:
**Rescheduling Biometrics Appointment:**

• **Online**: Through your USCIS online account (if available)
• **By Phone**: Call USCIS at 1-800-375-5283
• **Valid Reasons**: Medical emergency, work conflict, travel
• **Advance Notice**: Reschedule as early as possible
• **Documentation**: May need to provide supporting evidence

**Walk-in Policy**: Some Application Support Centers accept walk-ins, but appointment is preferred.

**Important**: Don't miss your appointment without contacting USCIS first.

categories.pattern: HOW LONG AFTER BIOMETRICS IS INTERVIEW
categories.template:
**Timeline After Biometrics:**

**Varies by Application Type:**
• **Naturalization (N-400)**: 6-18 months for interview
• **Adjustment of Status (I-485)**: 8-24 months for interview
• **Asylum**: 6-12 months for interview
• **Work Authorization**: No interview required

**Factors Affecting Timeline:**
• Service center workload
• Background check completion
• Case complexity
• Interview scheduling availability

**Check processing times** for your specific form and office for current estimates.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I APPLY FOR ADVANCE PAROLE
categories.template:
**Advance Parole Application (Form I-131):**

• **When to File**: Before you need to travel
• **Processing Time**: 4-6 months
• **Required Documents**: I-131 form, photos, supporting evidence
• **Fee**: Check current I-131 filing fee
• **Valid Reasons**: Emergency, humanitarian, business
• **Combo Card**: Often combined with work authorization

**Emergency Requests**: Expedited processing available for urgent travel needs.

**Don't Travel**: Without approved advance parole if required for your case.

categories.pattern: WHAT IS ADVANCE PAROLE
categories.template:
**Advance Parole Explained:**

• **Definition**: Permission to return to US after temporary travel abroad
• **Who Needs It**: Certain applicants with pending cases
• **Form**: I-131 Application for Travel Document
• **Validity**: Usually 1-2 years from issue date
• **Multiple Entries**: Allows multiple trips during validity period

**Important**: Having advance parole doesn't guarantee re-entry - CBP makes final decision.

**Alternative**: Some visa holders don't need advance parole (H-1B, L-1, etc.)

categories.pattern: CAN I USE EXPIRED ADVANCE PAROLE
categories.template:
**Expired Advance Parole:**

• **Cannot Use**: Expired advance parole is not valid for travel
• **Re-entry Risk**: May be denied entry to the US
• **Abandoned Application**: Could abandon pending I-485
• **New Application**: Must file new I-131 for future travel

**If Currently Abroad**: Contact US embassy/consulate for guidance

**Prevention**: File for renewal well before expiration if continued travel needed.

**Emergency**: Contact USCIS for emergency travel document if urgent travel required.

categories.pattern: DIFFERENCE BETWEEN ADVANCE PAROLE AND VISA
categories.template:
**Advance Parole vs. Visa:**

**Advance Parole:**
• Temporary travel permission
• For pending application holders
• Allows return to continue case
• Not a visa or status

**Visa:**
• Permission to enter US
• Grants specific status
• Issued by US consulates abroad
• Different categories (tourist, work, etc.)

**Key Difference**: Advance parole is for people already in the US with pending cases; visas are for people seeking to enter the US.

**Some people** may have both valid visa and advance parole.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I PAY USCIS FEES
categories.template:
**USCIS Payment Methods:**

**Online Filing:**
• **Credit/Debit Cards**: Visa, MasterCard, American Express, Discover
• **Bank Transfer**: Direct debit from checking/savings account

**Paper Filing:**
• **Check**: Personal or cashier's check
• **Money Order**: US Postal Service or bank money order
• **Credit Card**: Using Form G-1450

**Make Payable To**: 'U.S. Department of Homeland Security'

**Fee Waivers**: Available for certain applicants who meet income requirements.

categories.pattern: CAN I GET A FEE WAIVER
categories.template:
**USCIS Fee Waiver Eligibility:**

**Qualify If You:**
• Receive means-tested benefits (SNAP, Medicaid, etc.)
• Household income at or below 150% of Federal Poverty Guidelines
• Financial hardship preventing fee payment

**Required Form**: I-912 Request for Fee Waiver

**Supporting Evidence:**
• Tax returns or transcripts
• Bank statements
• Benefit award letters
• Proof of income

**Not Available For**: All application types - check form instructions

**Reduced Fees**: Available for some applicants who don't qualify for full waiver.

categories.pattern: WHAT IF MY PAYMENT IS REJECTED
categories.template:
**If USCIS Rejects Your Payment:**

**Common Reasons:**
• Insufficient funds
• Incorrect fee amount
• Wrong payee name
• Expired credit card
• Bank processing issues

**USCIS Actions:**
• Returns entire application package
• Sends rejection notice
• No processing begins

**Your Response:**
• Correct payment issue
• Resubmit entire package
• Include new, correct payment
• Check current fee amounts

**Timeline**: Resubmit as soon as possible to avoid further delays.

categories.pattern: HOW MUCH ARE USCIS FEES
categories.template:
**Current USCIS Fees (check uscis.gov for updates):**

**Common Applications:**
• **N-400 (Naturalization)**: $725 ($640 + $85 biometrics)
• **I-485 (Green Card)**: $1,140-$1,225 (varies by age)
• **I-765 (Work Authorization)**: $410
• **I-131 (Travel Document)**: $575
• **I-90 (Green Card Renewal)**: $540 ($455 + $85 biometrics)
• **I-130 (Family Petition)**: $535

**Fees Change**: Check uscis.gov for current fee schedule

**Biometrics**: Additional $85 fee for most applications requiring biometrics

categories.pattern: CAN I PAY USCIS FEES IN INSTALLMENTS
categories.template:
**USCIS Fee Payment:**

• **Full Payment Required**: USCIS requires full fee payment at time of filing
• **No Installment Plans**: USCIS does not offer payment plans
• **Options If Cannot Pay Full Amount**:
  - Apply for fee waiver (Form I-912)
  - Apply for reduced fee (if eligible)
  - Wait until you can pay full amount

**Fee Waiver**: Available for qualifying low-income applicants

**Reduced Fees**: Available for some forms for qualifying applicants

**Plan Ahead**: Save money before filing to ensure you can pay required fees.

categories.pattern: WHAT IF USCIS DOESN'T RESPOND TO MY INQUIRY
categories.template:
**If USCIS Doesn't Respond:**

**Timeline Expectations:**
• **Case Inquiries**: 30 days for response
• **Phone Calls**: May have long wait times
• **Online Submissions**: Check your online account

**Follow-Up Actions:**
• **Resubmit Inquiry**: If no response after 30 days
• **Congressional Inquiry**: Contact your representative
• **Ombudsman**: Contact USCIS Ombudsman for systemic issues
• **Legal Help**: Consult immigration attorney

**Document Everything**: Keep records of all communications with USCIS

categories.pattern: I LOST MY GREEN CARD WHERE DO I DO
categories.template:
File **Form I-90, Application to Replace Permanent Resident Card**:

• **Online Filing**: Recommended at uscis.gov
• **By Mail**: Download form and mail to USCIS
• **Required Documents**: Copy of previous green card (if available), identity documents
• **Fee**: Check current I-90 filing fee
• **Processing Time**: Typically 10-13 months

**For Travel**: You may request expedited processing for travel emergencies.

categories.pattern: CAN I RENEW MY GREEN CARD
categories.template:
• Green Card Renewal Process (Form I-90):**

• **When to Renew**: Within 6 months of expiration
• **Online Filing**: Available at uscis.gov (recommended)
• **Required Documents**: Current green card, photos, supporting evidence
• **Fee**: Check current I-90 filing fee
• **Processing Time**: 10-13 months
• **Biometrics**: May be required

**Important**: Don't wait until your card expires to file for renewal.

categories.pattern: WHERE ARE THE FIELDS IN GREEN CARD FORM
categories.template:
**Key fields in Green Card forms (I-485 and I-90):**

**Personal Information:**
• Full legal name (as it appears on documents)
• Date and place of birth
• Country of birth and citizenship
• Social Security Number
• A-Number (if previously assigned)

**Contact Information:**
• Current mailing address
• Physical address (if different)
• Phone number and email

**Immigration History:**
• Date of entry to US
• Current immigration status
• Previous USCIS case numbers
• Travel history (trips outside US)

**Background Information:**
• Employment history
• Education background
• Criminal history (if any)
• Previous marriages/divorces

**Supporting Documents Required:**
• Birth certificate
• Passport photos
• Medical examination (if required)
• Financial support evidence

**Important**: Complete all fields accurately and provide supporting documentation as specified in the form instructions.

categories.pattern: WHERE DOCUMENTS DO I NEED FOR NATURALIZATION
categories.template:
**Required Documents for Naturalization (N-400):**

• **Form N-400** (completed and signed)
• **Copy of green card** (front and back)
• **Two passport-style photos**
• **Copy of marriage certificate** (if applicable)
• **Divorce decrees** (if applicable)
• **Tax returns** (last 5 years)
• **Travel records** (trips outside US)
• **Selective Service registration** (males 18-25)

**Additional documents may be required** based on your specific situation. Review Form N-400 instructions carefully.

categories.pattern: CAN I CHECK MY ELIGIBILITY FOR CITIZENSHIP
categories.template:
• Check your citizenship eligibility:**

• **USCIS Eligibility Tool**: Available at uscis.gov
• **Form N-400 Instructions**: Detailed eligibility requirements
• **General Requirements**: 5 years as permanent resident (3 if married to US citizen)
• **Physical Presence**: At least 30 months in US during 5-year period
• **Continuous Residence**: No trips over 6 months
• **Good Moral Character**: Required for eligibility period
• **English and Civics**: Must pass tests

**Consult an immigration attorney** for complex situations or questions about eligibility.

categories.pattern: WHERE IS THE NATURALIZATION TEST
categories.template:
**Naturalization Test Components:**

**English Test:**
• **Speaking**: Assessed during interview
• **Reading**: Read 1-3 sentences aloud
• **Writing**: Write 1-3 sentences

**Civics Test:**
• **Questions**: Up to 10 questions from 100 possible
• **Pass Score**: Answer 6 out of 10 correctly
• **Topics**: American history and civics
• **Study Materials**: Available at uscis.gov

**Exemptions Available:**
• Age and time as permanent resident
• Medical disabilities
• Check USCIS website for specific exemption criteria

categories.pattern: CAN I CHECK MY CITIZENSHIP INTERVIEW DATE
categories.template:
• Check your naturalization interview date:**

• **USCIS Online Account**: Most reliable source for updates
• **Mail Notice**: USCIS will send interview notice by mail
• **Case Status Tool**: https://egov.uscis.gov/casestatus/
• **Timeline**: Usually scheduled 6-12 months after filing N-400
• **Notice Contents**: Date, time, location, documents to bring

**Interview Notice includes**: Date, time, location, and documents to bring.

**Rescheduling**: Contact USCIS if you cannot attend your scheduled interview.

categories.pattern: WHERE HAPPENS AT CITIZENSHIP INTERVIEW
categories.template:
**Naturalization Interview Process:**

**Before Interview:**
• Arrive early with all required documents
• Bring original documents and copies
• Review your N-400 application

**During Interview:**
• **Oath**: Swear to tell the truth
• **Application Review**: Officer reviews your N-400
• **Background Questions**: About your application and background
• **English Test**: Speaking, reading, writing
• **Civics Test**: Up to 10 questions about US history/civics

**After Interview:**
• **Decision**: Approved, denied, or continued
• **Next Steps**: Oath ceremony scheduling (if approved)

**Typical Duration**: 20-30 minutes

categories.template:
• Work Permit Renewal (Form I-765):**

• **When to File**: 150-180 days before expiration
• **Same Process**: File new I-765 application
• **Required Documents**: Current EAD, supporting evidence, photos
• **Fee**: Full filing fee required
• **Processing Time**: 3-5 months
• **Automatic Extension**: May be available for certain categories

**Don't wait**: File well before your current EAD expires to avoid work authorization gaps.

categories.pattern: CAN I APPLY FOR A WORK PERMIT

File • Form I-765, Application for Employment Authorization**:

• **Online Filing**: Available at uscis.gov (recommended)

• **Required**: Copy of I-94, passport, supporting evidence for your category
• **Photos**: Two passport-style photos
• **Fee**: Check current I-765 filing fee
• **Processing Time**: Typically 3-5 months

**Expedite requests** available for certain circumstances.

categories.pattern: WHERE IS EAD CATEGORY

• **(a)(10)**: Withholding of removal
• **(c)(33)**: DACA recipients
• **(a)(5)**: Refugees

• Eligibility requirements
• Required supporting documents
• Processing times
• Renewal procedures

• Advance Parole Application (Form I-131):**

• **Fee**: Check current I-131 filing fee

categories.pattern: WHERE IS ADVANCE PAROLE
categories.template:
**Advance Parole Explained:**

• **Definition**: Permission to return to US after temporary travel abroad
• **Who Needs It**: Certain applicants with pending cases
• **Form**: I-131 Application for Travel Document
• **Validity**: Usually 1-2 years from issue date
• **Multiple Entries**: Allows multiple trips during validity period

**Important**: Having advance parole doesn't guarantee re-entry - CBP makes final decision.

**Alternative**: Some visa holders don't need advance parole (H-1B, L-1, etc.)

categories.pattern: WHERE IF MY PAYMENT IS REJECTED
categories.template:
**If USCIS Rejects Your Payment:**

**Common Reasons:**
• Insufficient funds
• Incorrect fee amount
• Wrong payee name
• Expired credit card
• Bank processing issues

**USCIS Actions:**
• Returns entire application package
• Sends rejection notice
• No processing begins

**Your Response:**
• Correct payment issue
• Resubmit entire package
• Include new, correct payment
• Check current fee amounts

**Timeline**: Resubmit as soon as possible to avoid further delays.

categories.pattern: CAN I PAY USCIS FEES

• **Money Order**: US Postal Service or bank money order
• **Credit Card**: Using Form G-1450

**Make Payable To**: 'U.S. Department of Homeland Security'

**Fee Waivers**: Available for certain applicants who meet income requirements.

categories.pattern: HOW DO I PETITION FOR MY SPOUSE
categories.template:
**Petitioning for Your Spouse (Form I-130):**

• **US Citizen**: Can petition immediately
• **Permanent Resident**: Subject to visa availability
• **Required Documents**: Marriage certificate, proof of citizenship/residence
• **Processing Time**: 12-33 months depending on status
• **Next Steps**: Consular processing or adjustment of status

**Additional Forms**: I-864 Affidavit of Support required

**Conditional Residence**: 2-year conditional status if married less than 2 years

categories.pattern: HOW DO I BRING MY PARENTS TO US
categories.template:
**Petitioning for Parents (Form I-130):**

• **Only US Citizens**: Can petition for parents
• **Immediate Relatives**: No visa number limitations
• **Required Documents**: Birth certificate showing relationship, proof of citizenship
• **Processing Time**: 12-18 months
• **Both Parents**: Need separate I-130 for each parent
• **Step-Parents**: Eligible if marriage occurred before petitioner's 18th birthday

**Financial Support**: I-864 Affidavit of Support required

categories.pattern: HOW DO I PETITION FOR MY SPOUSE
categories.template:
**Petitioning for Your Spouse (Form I-130):**

• **US Citizen**: Can petition immediately
• **Permanent Resident**: Subject to visa availability
• **Required Documents**: Marriage certificate, proof of citizenship/residence
• **Processing Time**: 12-33 months depending on status
• **Next Steps**: Consular processing or adjustment of status

**Additional Forms**: I-864 Affidavit of Support required

**Conditional Residence**: 2-year conditional status if married less than 2 years

categories.pattern: HOW DO I BRING MY PARENTS TO US
categories.template:
**Petitioning for Parents (Form I-130):**

• **Only US Citizens**: Can petition for parents
• **Immediate Relatives**: No visa number limitations
• **Required Documents**: Birth certificate showing relationship, proof of citizenship
• **Processing Time**: 12-18 months
• **Both Parents**: Need separate I-130 for each parent
• **Step-Parents**: Eligible if marriage occurred before petitioner's 18th birthday

**Financial Support**: I-864 Affidavit of Support required

categories.pattern: HOW DO I PETITION FOR MY CHILD
categories.template:
**Petitioning for Your Child (Form I-130):**

• **Unmarried Children Under 21**: Immediate relatives (US citizens only)
• **Married Children**: Family preference categories
• **Adult Children**: Different categories based on marital status
• **Required Documents**: Birth certificate, proof of relationship
• **Age Out Protection**: Child Status Protection Act may apply

**Processing varies** by petitioner status and child's age/marital status

categories.pattern: HOW DO I APPLY FOR ASYLUM
categories.template:
**Asylum Application Process (Form I-589):**

• **Filing Deadline**: Within 1 year of arrival (with exceptions)
• **Required Form**: I-589 Application for Asylum
• **No Fee**: No filing fee for asylum applications
• **Supporting Evidence**: Country condition evidence, personal testimony
• **Interview**: Required with asylum officer
• **Legal Representation**: Highly recommended

**Exceptions to 1-Year Rule**: Changed circumstances, extraordinary circumstances

**Family Members**: Can include spouse and unmarried children under 21

categories.pattern: WHAT IS THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN ASYLUM AND REFUGEE
categories.template:
**Asylum vs. Refugee Status:**

**Asylum:**
• Apply while in the United States
• Must apply within 1 year of arrival
• Form I-589
• Interview with asylum officer

**Refugee:**
• Apply from outside the United States
• Referred by UNHCR or US Embassy
• Resettlement program
• No 1-year deadline

**Both require**: Well-founded fear of persecution based on protected grounds

categories.pattern: HOW DO I GET AN H1B VISA
categories.template:
**H-1B Visa Process:**

• **Employer Petition**: Employer must file Form I-129
• **Specialty Occupation**: Requires bachelor's degree or equivalent
• **Annual Cap**: Limited number available each year (lottery system)
• **Labor Condition Application**: Department of Labor filing required
• **Duration**: Initially 3 years, extendable to 6 years total

**Lottery System**: Registration required during filing period (usually March)

**Premium Processing**: Available for faster adjudication

categories.pattern: HOW DO I APPLY FOR EMPLOYMENT GREEN CARD
categories.template:
**Employment-Based Green Card Process:**

**Step 1: Labor Certification (PERM)**
• Employer files with Department of Labor
• Tests US job market
• 6-12 months processing

**Step 2: I-140 Petition**
• Employer files with USCIS
• Establishes qualification
• 4-8 months processing

**Step 3: Adjustment of Status (I-485)**
• File when priority date is current
• Final step to get green card
• 8-24 months processing

**Priority Date**: Determines when you can file I-485

categories.pattern: HOW DO I GET AN F1 STUDENT VISA
categories.template:
**F-1 Student Visa Process:**

• **School Acceptance**: Must be accepted by SEVP-approved school
• **Form I-20**: School issues I-20 Certificate of Eligibility
• **SEVIS Fee**: Pay $350 SEVIS fee online
• **Visa Application**: Apply at US consulate in home country
• **Financial Evidence**: Prove ability to pay tuition and living expenses
• **Interview**: Required at US consulate

**Timing**: Apply after receiving I-20, no more than 120 days before program start

**Entry**: Can enter US up to 30 days before program start date

categories.pattern: WHAT IS OPT FOR F1 STUDENTS
categories.template:
**Optional Practical Training (OPT) for F-1 Students:**

• **Work Authorization**: Allows F-1 students to work in field of study
• **Duration**: 12 months (24 months additional for STEM)
• **Application**: File Form I-765 with USCIS
• **Timing**: Apply within 90 days of program completion
• **DSO Recommendation**: Required from school's international office

**STEM Extension**: Additional 24 months for qualifying degrees

**Employment**: Must be related to field of study

**Unemployment**: Limited to 90 days total during OPT period

categories.pattern: HOW DO I GET A TOURIST VISA TO US
categories.template:
**B-2 Tourist Visa Application:**

• **Form DS-160**: Complete online application
• **Visa Fee**: Pay required application fee
• **Interview**: Schedule at US consulate/embassy
• **Supporting Documents**: Proof of ties to home country, financial support
• **Purpose**: Tourism, visiting family/friends, medical treatment
• **Duration**: Usually 6 months per entry

**Required Documents**: Passport, photo, DS-160 confirmation, fee receipt

**Interview Tips**: Be prepared to explain purpose and ties to home country

categories.pattern: CAN I EXTEND MY TOURIST VISA
categories.template:
**Extending B-2 Tourist Status (Form I-539):**

• **File Before Expiration**: Must apply before I-94 expires
• **Valid Reasons**: Medical treatment, family emergency, other compelling reasons
• **Supporting Evidence**: Documentation of circumstances requiring extension
• **Fee**: Check current I-539 filing fee
• **Processing Time**: 4-8 months
• **Stay Authorized**: Can remain while application is pending

**Important**: Extensions are discretionary - not guaranteed

**Multiple Extensions**: Generally not recommended

categories.pattern: WHAT IS ON THE CITIZENSHIP TEST
categories.template:
**Naturalization Test Components:**

**English Test:**
• **Speaking**: Assessed during interview
• **Reading**: Read 1-3 sentences aloud
• **Writing**: Write 1-3 sentences

**Civics Test:**
• **Questions**: Up to 10 questions from 100 possible
• **Pass Score**: Answer 6 out of 10 correctly
• **Topics**: American history and civics
• **Study Materials**: Available at uscis.gov

**Exemptions Available**: Based on age and time as permanent resident

categories.pattern: HOW DO I STUDY FOR CITIZENSHIP TEST
categories.template:
**Citizenship Test Study Resources:**

**Official USCIS Materials:**
• **Study Guide**: Free at uscis.gov
• **100 Civics Questions**: Complete list with answers
• **Practice Tests**: Online practice available
• **Mobile Apps**: USCIS Civics Test Study Tools

**Study Tips:**
• Review American history and government
• Practice English reading and writing
• Take practice tests regularly
• Join citizenship classes if available

**Free Resources**: Libraries often offer citizenship classes

categories.pattern: WHAT HAPPENS IN IMMIGRATION COURT
categories.template:
**Immigration Court Process:**

**Master Calendar Hearing:**
• Initial appearance before judge
• Review charges and allegations
• Enter plea (admit or deny charges)
• Request relief if eligible

**Individual Hearing:**
• Present evidence and testimony
• Legal arguments
• Judge makes final decision

**Possible Outcomes**: Removal, relief granted, voluntary departure

**Legal Representation**: Highly recommended but not provided by government

categories.pattern: HOW DO I FIND AN IMMIGRATION LAWYER
categories.template:
**Finding Immigration Legal Help:**

**Qualified Attorneys:**
• **State Bar Associations**: Lawyer referral services
• **AILA**: American Immigration Lawyers Association directory
• **Legal Aid**: Non-profit organizations for low-income individuals
• **Pro Bono**: Free legal services programs

**Avoid Immigration Scams:**
• Only licensed attorneys can represent you
• Avoid notarios and immigration consultants
• Verify attorney credentials with state bar

**Questions to Ask**: Experience, fees, case strategy, timeline
